<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is a half-square triangle in quilting?", answer: "A half-square triangle, or HST, is a square unit made up of two right triangles sewn together along their long diagonal edge. HSTs are one of the most common building blocks in quilting and can be arranged into hundreds of classic patterns including pinwheels, flying geese, broken dishes, and sawtooth stars. They are beloved because they introduce color and movement without complex piecing." },
  { question: "Which HST method is most accurate?", answer: "The 2-at-a-time method is generally the most accurate because each HST is sewn and cut individually with fewer bias edges exposed during pressing. The 4-at-a-time and 8-at-a-time methods are faster but produce HSTs with all four sides on the bias, which stretch during pressing and usually need to be squared up to the finished size plus half an inch. For precise piecing, choose 2-at-a-time and always square up before assembling blocks." },
  { question: "Why add 7/8 inch to the finished size?", answer: "The magic 7/8 rule exists because the diagonal of a square equals the square's side times the square root of 2, and you need a 1/4-inch seam allowance on both sides of the diagonal cut. The math works out so that adding 7/8 inch to the finished HST size gives you a cut square that, after sewing and cutting, produces two HSTs at exactly the finished size plus a 1/4-inch seam allowance. It is one of the cleanest constants in quilting math." },
  { question: "Should I square up my HSTs?", answer: "Yes, squaring up HSTs to the unfinished size (finished size plus 1/2 inch for seam allowances) is the single biggest accuracy improvement you can make in quilting. Use a square ruler with a 45-degree line and trim each HST to the correct unfinished size before assembling blocks. This step corrects stretch, uneven seam allowances, and small cutting errors, and it makes the final quilt top lie flat without distortion." },
  { question: "Can I make HSTs from scraps?", answer: "Yes, HSTs are a fantastic way to use scrap fabric. Sort your scraps by color value, cut them to matching square sizes, and pair lights with darks for maximum contrast. The 2-at-a-time method works well with scraps because you only need two matching squares per pair. Scrappy HSTs create the warm, eclectic look of traditional utility quilts and give you a built-in reason to keep every small piece of fabric you have." }
]) %>

